</span></span>

</p/><p><strong>Summary: </strong>
Walking through the mental geography of what I&rsquo;ve read along with the serendipity of exploration.
</p>
        <p>Through my reading rolled the term <em>inner library</em>: the collection of
books/stories that we carry within us.  I’ve read several hundred books,
thousands of blog posts, numerous short-stories, graphic novels, and so forth.</p>
<p>And Tolkien dominates my <em>inner library</em>.  Not that I’ve read Tolkien so very
often but because, as Terry Pratchet once quipped:</p>
<blockquote class="quote epigraph" data-id="jrr-tolkien-has-become-a-sort-of-mountain">
<p>
J.R.R. Tolkien has become a sort of mountain, appearing in all subsequent
fantasy in the way that Mt. Fuji appears so often in Japanese prints. Sometimes
it’s big and up close. Sometimes it’s a shape on the horizon. Sometimes it’s not
there at all, which means that the artist either has made a deliberate decision
against the mountain, which is interesting in itself, or is in fact standing on
Mt. Fuji.
</p>
<footer>&#8213; Terry Pratchett</footer></blockquote>
<p>Fantasy was mostly what I read during the first 40 years of life; long
dominating and thus itself full of echoes of Tolkien.</p>
<p>I’m working to curate that <em>inner library</em>; finding more women voices, as well as
those of other cultures and frames.  I want this <em>inner library</em> that I carry to
be broad and interesting.  To move me further towards empathy and understanding;
to help me gain access to more of myself.</p>
<p>I wrote Twenty Books that Have Stayed with Me; those are the front-faced books
of that library.  Below is a reproduction of that list, though not the reasons:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite data-id="8EC50DA2-394A-4002-BA2D-C4B47C15D725">all about love</cite> by bell hooks</li>
<li><cite data-id="B847DB2B-8DB9-40CB-8ED9-5A2D38D875C6">Drive Your Plow over the Bones of the Dead</cite> by Olga Tokarczuk</li>
<li><cite data-id="AB3BE8D6-8D85-460F-8D91-A6B3128713C0">Dune</cite> by Frank Herbert</li>
<li><cite data-id="CA30F40E-0405-4027-A73E-DAA24FD52A33">Gilgamesh Retold</cite> by Jenny Lewis</li>
<li><cite data-id="DCC56C4D-F615-4412-BE34-AA6F81BB064A">How to Take Smart Notes</cite> by Sönke Ahrens</li>
<li><cite data-id="0733A24C-254F-4DA8-9003-80A24FC58AF2">M Train</cite> by Patti Smith</li>
<li><cite data-id="6DA6D508-9DB5-42D4-A105-6DBD83C309E5">On Writing</cite> by Stephen King</li>
<li><cite data-id="F7A9E56F-1FF2-43DF-B6EB-412FDD53FA00">Ragnarok</cite> by Antonia Bryant</li>
<li><cite data-id="472C1DBD-E0EB-4510-96D4-E474DF0C313E">Siddhartha</cite> by Herman Hesse</li>
<li><cite data-id="4730AADE-0F37-4198-B657-D97507B7E5C5">The Broken Sword</cite> by Poul Anderson</li>
<li><cite data-id="2364C428-BFD5-4DF2-949A-5ECA5988E97F">The Dark Fantastic</cite> by Ebony Elizabeth Thomas</li>
<li><cite data-id="B716B561-9CFB-4712-B247-848A312BE175">The Fellowship of the Ring</cite> by J.R.R. Tolkien</li>
<li><cite data-id="48BC2291-5206-4977-AA9E-1B8C8E089DCA">The Left Hand of Darkness</cite> by Ursula K Le Guin</li>
<li><cite data-id="219EDD96-3C39-4CD5-9CB1-AA296408909D">The Living Mountain</cite> by Nan Shephard</li>
<li><cite data-id="2436E81C-1F2F-4EA0-8FE1-D57A97B4F26A">The Lord of the Rings</cite> by Wayne G. Hammond and Christina Scull</li>
<li><cite data-id="E247BA67-4874-436C-A103-373A60D1483A">The Odyssey</cite> by Emily Wilson</li>
<li><cite data-id="7904CE86-1A82-4FCB-B0DB-BCBCE04C2811">The Origins of Creativity</cite> by Edward O. Wilson</li>
<li><cite data-id="A1269611-7FD7-4215-91C2-0B65CBAE2E85">Tragedy, The Greeks, and Us</cite> by Simon Critchley</li>
<li><cite data-id="0827D907-E295-4D6E-BC0B-C8FF16BA5A05">Upstream</cite> by Mary Oliver</li>
<li><cite data-id="A6E49A97-C58B-44B3-A755-1CA627C0B8E5">Wanderlust</cite> by Rebecca Solnit</li>
</ul>
<p>I chuckle as Nan Shephard’s <cite data-id="219EDD96-3C39-4CD5-9CB1-AA296408909D">The Living Mountain</cite> is almost certainly not
influenced by Tolkien nor influenced Tolkien<small class="side-container">
  <span class="side-label"><span class="hidden">(</span>Sidenote<span class="hidden">:</span></span>
  <span class="side" role="note"> Written around the time of the release of <a href="work:ad1e6319-b4f2-4f00-b94f-1ac0834018ab">«The Hobbit»</a>, set aside for
several decades, and then published.<span class="hidden">)</span></span>
</small>
.  It is about Shephard living
amongst the Cairngorm mountains of Scotland.  Yet a mountain looms.</p>
<p>And Rebecca Solnit’s <cite data-id="A6E49A97-C58B-44B3-A755-1CA627C0B8E5">Wanderlust</cite>, and its details of the social power of
walking, reinforcing the only path available to Frodo…to walk and walk.</p>
<p>Tolkien permeates.  Yet, his early desires (see Other Hands) were for others to
join in his sub-creation.  Copyright and estate management blocks that
possibility; but Tolkien showed his work, in that he drew upon the myriad of
older stories.  Giving shape to something mythical and adding to those
foundations.</p>
<p>And its not just the fantastical of Tolkien, there’s wordsmithing, connecting
oldness to present; walking with us as we explore a world (of myth) that could
almost be.  Of trees and flowers, stone and fungus, poem and the chain mail
song.  A world alive.</p>
<p>As I look to that list, I see clearly that I’m interested in myth making.  That
is being in conversations with our myths.  And my desire to broaden my reading
is recognizing that I want a more robust <em>inner library</em>; a deeper connection to a
broader world.  To hear the folklore that feed our world.  Knowing that often
women were the keepers of that folklore; yet it was often men who codified them.</p>
<p>And is that codification much like a dissection?  The subject is, at first,
alive, then very much not.</p>
<p>I once asked a well-read friend if I should read Proust, he chuckled and said
“Maybe, though I suspect you’ve read enough dead white guys.”  I don’t know if
I’ll get around to Proust, but I’m intrigued.</p>
<p>And on that I note, I was curious about what I’ve read (thus far) for <time datetime="2025" title="2025">2025</time>.  And
the majority, by my quick scan, are books by neither dead nor living white guys.</p>
<ul>
<li><cite data-id="fee4ffa7-1d45-46e7-86f1-af203b92f54b">Aflame</cite> by Pico Iyer</li>
