<p>I tumble from interest to interest, often having two or three books running
concurrently.  And they interweave, tributaries that gather and fill the body of
water that is this <em>inner library</em>.</p>
<p>As I write this, I think of <cite data-id="55a32435-c012-4892-be9a-ac00b5b17204">Piranesi</cite> as most representative of that <em>inner
library</em>.  Large statues—Tolkienesque—fill the myriad of rooms.  Waters waters
flood and recede, bringing sustenance to the person inside.  Yet to remain there
is to forget and be lost to the world.  The titular character does find exit,
but also returns to draw comfort and understanding from this place of solitude.</p>
<p>Solitude.</p>
<p>On a lark at the library, I picked up <cite data-id="1f28328c-be96-453d-a9a8-9b921c39fd8a">The Little Book of Solitude</cite>,
which lead me to <cite data-id="fee4ffa7-1d45-46e7-86f1-af203b92f54b">Aflame</cite>, and reconnected me to Thich Nhat Hanh.</p>
<p>And how a conversation a few years ago in a bar drew my attention to Haruki
Murakami.  <cite data-id="588d8c62-e79a-4ffe-99f3-a73aba315a8e">Spring, Summer, Asteroid, Bird</cite> gave a frame to consider Murakami;
and <cite data-id="5dd8020b-640b-420d-ae24-84169585038c">To Fight Against this Age</cite> identified Kafka, by second-hand account, as
vital.  So I read my first Kafka novel: to understand Kafkaesque and to “unlock“
<cite data-id="kafka-on-the-shore-by-haruki-murakami">Kafka on the Shore</cite>.</p>
<p>Throughout <time datetime="2025" title="2025">this year</time> of reading—books and otherwise—names keep resurfacing:
Alice Walker, Audre Lorde, George Orwell, Hannah Arendt, Henry David Thoreau,
Toni Morrison, Ursula K Le Guin, and Václav Havel to name a few.</p>
<p>For reading I’m not setting down a curriculum, knowing that my interests flow
organically; and it is from there serendipity.  And for myself, I can most
easily find serendipity, looking at the neighbors of books I’ve found
interesting.</p>
<p>It was my library’s community read schedule <cite data-id="ISBN-9780199567690">Babbitt</cite> and two other Sinclair
Lewis books, that left me scratching my head.  Three Sinclair Lewis books?  Then
having read <cite data-id="ISBN-9780199567690">Babbitt</cite> I could see why.  I also learned that Tolkien drew
inspiration from <cite data-id="ISBN-9780199567690">Babbitt</cite> in creating Bilbo Baggins and Hobbits in general.</p>
<p>Serendipity.</p>

